davidkpiano:
If you do develop in Angular, would you just rip this stuff out when you went to production?
I do develop in AngularJS and I can see the utility of using this in development, but yeah, I'd rip it out in production.
Suggestion: why not group animations? If I do this:
```
animation: fade
```
then that would signify that I want a simple fade in/out animation for entrance/exit. It's unlikely that I'm going to do anything crazy like:
```
animationIn: fadeIn
animationOut: slideOutLeft

```
but I do appreciate the option to do that.
. @gakimball @whodidthis brings up a valid concern. I know that AngularJS is the current hotness, but coupling components strongly to AngularJS directives makes them very inflexible for other framerworks, such as Ember, Knockout, etc., and even jQuery (not a framework, but still).
If the components uniformly reacted to change of state (and this can be an attribute or class, doesn't matter), it would make integration into other frameworks (or even vanilla JS) much, much simpler. Here's a semi-pseudocode example:
html
<div class="panel">This panel won't slide out, yet.</div>
<div class="panel active">This panel will slide out, since its state is now active.</div>
``` scss
@mixin panel(... $active: '.active') {
  // inactive transform state; e.g. transform: translateX(-300px);
#{$active} {
    // active transform state; e.g. transform: translateX(0);
  }
}
```
And then in JS, you can use any framework/library to simply activate the state of the component by adding a class/changing an attribute, and let the CSS take care of the rest.
. In general, do you think the panel/block hybrid will be useful?
Sort of. The concept of a block responsively becoming a "panel" and vice-versa is very useful, and a great alternative to stacking. However, to me, the off-canvas component and panel are very similar, and having two separate components describe similar functionality and presentation (correct me if I'm wrong) seems redundant. A panel can be thought of as an off-canvas component that doesn't push its sibling, and relative to either the viewport or its parent.
Are the extra classes required confusing?
Probably confusing, probably a bit unnecessary, and a little too restrictive. A simple set of style rules inside .panel.block would be sufficient to "cancel out" block/panel styles for specified media queries. And now for the "restrictive" part...
Would you ever want a block on a smaller screen and a panel on a larger screen?
Yes, and more (sorry for being greedy). Here are some scenarios:
- I want a panel that's almost full width in mobile portrait mode, but only half width in landscape mode. (this is the standard, I believe, for Google Android apps)
- I want a panel in desktop mode because, now that I have more real estate, I can do two important sections side-by-side, so the respective viewports for those sections might still be small.
- Continuing the above, those two side-by-side important sections are stacked in mobile, so it's more appropriate to display the medium-panels as a block in mobile.
- I want a panel in mobile portrait mode, but a side-by-side block in landscape mode.
And I'm sure I can think of others. These scenarios hint that panels could be breakpoint-aware, just like grid blocks:
- small-panel - 90% (or 11/12 or whatever) width panel for a small breakpoint
- medium-panel - 50% width panel for a medium breakpoint
And since specificity would be determined by the respective media queries, the panels would easily override .block styling.
. Have you guys considered consolidating classes? Let's say you wanted a 6-column panel when small and a 4-column block when medium. That sounds like only two classes to me:
html
<div class="
  panel-small-6
  block-medium-4
"></div>
To not produce an extreme amount of raw CSS output in order to accomplish this, you can use what I call "prefix selectors" to define the base styles for the parent components:
``` css
[class^="panel-"], [class*=" panel-"] {
  // base panel styles go here
}
@media ... {
  [class^="panel-small-"], [class*=" panel-small-"] {
    // media query specific panel styles go here
  }
.panel-small-6 { ... }
  .panel-small-7 { ... }
}
```
I've had no specificity issues when doing this in personal projects. Let me know what you think!
. @zurbrandon You're right, as the panels don't necessarily interact with the grid, maybe having their sizes grid-based is a bit excessive. I like the idea of them being on a custom-sized basis (using SASS variables) with three (proposed) standard sizes:
- $panel-length: 300px or whatever the default size is
- $panel-full-length: 90% (or 11/12) of width/height by default
- $panel-half-length: 50% of width/height by default
So you'll have that standard size unless the user specifies if it should be a full- or half-length panel. So here would be an example mixin:
``` scss
@mixin panel(
    $length: $panel-length,
    $position: left,
    $active-selector: '.is-active',
    $breakpoint: all
) {
    @include breakpoint($breakpoint) { // or any media-query mixin
        position: absolute;
    @if $position == left or $position == right {
        width: $length;
    @else if $position == top or $position == bottom {
        height: $length;
    }

    @if $position == left {
        top: 0;
        left: 0;
        transform: translateX(-100%);
    } // etc. for right, top, bottom

    &#{$active-selector} {
        transform: translate(0, 0);
    }
}

}
```
